const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "How to Talk to Your Doctor About Sexual Health",
  "description": "Overcome embarrassment and advocate for yourself. Learn what questions to ask and how to find sex-positive healthcare providers.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "The Nookie Nook"
  },
  "mainEntity": {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do doctors judge you for asking about sex?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Medical professionals are trained to view sexual health as a standard part of overall healthcare. A good doctor will not judge you for asking questions about STIs, pleasure, or contraception."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What should I do if my doctor is dismissive of my concerns?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You have the right to seek a second opinion. If a provider is dismissive of your pain or concerns, or uses shaming language, it is entirely acceptable to find a new, sex-positive provider."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What information does my doctor actually need to know?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "They need to know the types of sex you are having (oral, anal, vaginal), the number and gender(s) of your partners, and whether you use barrier methods, as this determines which tests and screenings you need."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
};

export const meta = {
  title: "Talking to Your Doctor About Sexual Health | The Nookie Nook",
  description: "Overcome embarrassment, learn what to ask, and advocate for yourself. A guide to finding sex-positive and inclusive healthcare.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---
<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="Talking to Your Doctor About Sexual Health | The Nookie Nook"
  description="Overcome embarrassment, learn what to ask, and advocate for yourself. A guide to finding sex-positive and inclusive healthcare."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/guide-talking-to-doctor"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>How to Talk to Your Doctor</h1>
      <p>Advocating for your sexual health without shame or embarrassment.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Part of our <a href="/sites/nookienook/sexual-health-guide">Comprehensive Sexual Health Guide</a> series.</p>

      <p>For many people, bringing up sexual health with a doctor is incredibly anxiety-inducing. Societal stigma, fear of judgment, or past negative experiences can make these conversations difficult. However, your sexual health is deeply connected to your overall well-being, and having an open dialogue with a healthcare provider is essential.</p>

      <h2>Overcoming the Embarrassment</h2>
      <p>Remember this foundational truth: <strong>Medical professionals have seen and heard it all.</strong> To a doctor, discussing an STI exposure, erectile dysfunction, or vaginal pain is no different than discussing a sore throat or a sprained ankle. It is simply human biology.</p>
      <p>If you feel nervous, it is perfectly okay to name it: <em>"I'm feeling a bit anxious to bring this up, but I have a question about my sexual health."</em> A good doctor will immediately recognize your vulnerability and work to make you comfortable.</p>

      <h2>What Your Doctor Needs to Know</h2>
      <p>To provide you with the correct tests, advice, and prescriptions, your doctor relies on your honesty. Being vague can lead to missed diagnoses. Be prepared to discuss:</p>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The types of sex you are having:</strong> Oral, anal, and vaginal sex carry different risks and require different testing methods (e.g., throat or rectal swabs).</li>
          <li><strong>Your partners:</strong> The number of partners you have and their genders can influence your risk profile for certain infections.</li>
          <li><strong>Contraception and protection:</strong> Whether you use condoms, dental dams, or hormonal birth control consistently.</li>
          <li><strong>Any pain or discomfort:</strong> Do not normalize pain during sex. If it hurts, tell them.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Questions You Should Ask</h2>
      <p>You are an active participant in your healthcare. Write your questions down before the appointment so you don't forget them in the moment. Consider asking:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>"Which STI tests are included in the 'standard panel' here? Are you testing for herpes and syphilis?"</em></li>
        <li><em>"Given my sexual activity, how often should I be getting tested?"</em></li>
        <li><em>"What are my options for contraception that don't contain estrogen?"</em></li>
        <li><em>"Is it normal to experience pain when I do [specific activity]?"</em></li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Finding a Sex-Positive Provider</h2>
      <p>Unfortunately, not all medical professionals are equally educated on modern sexual health, particularly regarding LGBTQ+ care, non-monogamous relationship structures, or sexual pain disorders. A "sex-positive" provider is one who is non-judgmental, affirming of your choices, and focused on your health rather than moralizing.</p>

      <h3>Red Flags in a Provider:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>They use shaming language about your number of partners.</li>
        <li>They dismiss your pain (e.g., "Just have a glass of wine and relax").</li>
        <li>They make assumptions about your sexual orientation or gender identity.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Green Flags in a Provider:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>They ask open-ended questions (e.g., "What are the genders of your partners?" instead of "Are you sexually active with men?").</li>
        <li>They clearly explain why they are asking certain questions or performing certain exams.</li>
        <li>They respect your boundaries and offer options for care.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>If you encounter red flags, <strong>you have the right to leave and find a new doctor.</strong> Resources like Planned Parenthood, local LGBTQ+ community centers, and online directories (like the GLMA Provider Directory) can help you find affirming care.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
